T1  - Human Capital as an Asset Class Implications from a General Equilibrium Model
PY  - 2015
Y1  - 2015/04/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhu073
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 28
IS  - 4
SP  - 978
EP  - 1023
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This paper derives the value and risk of aggregate human capital in a stochastic equilibrium model with Duffie-Epstein preferences. A three-factor asset-pricing model is derived, where the factors are the market, the capital share, and investment in human capital. When the model is calibrated to match the historical ratio of wages to consumption in the United States, the weight of human capital in aggregate wealth is estimated to be about 93%, well above most previous estimates, and human capital's riskiness is lower than that of the market portfolio.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhu073
ER  - 



